# 8. Main physics step

This function is the real engine:

```js
function a0_0x3d081c() { ... }
```

## What it does

### A. Pairwise inverse-square repulsion

For each pair of nodes:

- compute dx, dy, distance
- force = attraction / distanceÂ˛
- apply equal and opposite velocity changes

Despite the name `attraction`, this is actually used as **repulsion** because each node is pushed away from the other according to the sign of the difference vectors.

Equivalent clean code:

```js
for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
  for (let j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
    const dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
    const dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
    const dist = Math.sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy) || 1;

    const force = CONFIG.attraction / (dist * dist);
    const fx = dx / dist * force;
    const fy = dy / dist * force;

    nodes[i].vx += fx;
    nodes[i].vy += fy;
    nodes[j].vx -= fx;
    nodes[j].vy -= fy;
  }
}
```

### B. Spring constraints

For each edge:

- find node A and B
- compute current distance
- compare with rest length
- apply Hooke-like spring force with coefficient `k`

Equivalent:

```js
for (const edge of edges) {
  const a = getNodeById(edge.a);
  const b = getNodeById(edge.b);
  if (!a || !b) continue;

  const dx = b.x - a.x;
  const dy = b.y - a.y;
  const dist = Math.sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy) || 1;

  const stretch = dist - edge.rest;
  const force = (edge.k || CONFIG.frictionCoeff) * stretch;

  a.vx += dx / dist * force;
  a.vy += dy / dist * force;
  b.vx -= dx / dist * force;
  b.vy -= dy / dist * force;
}
```

### C. Damping and drift to center

For each node:

- `vx *= 0.92`
- `vy *= 0.92`
- `x += vx`
- `y += vy`
- add weak force pulling toward `(400, 300)`

Equivalent:

```js
for (const n of nodes) {
  n.vx += (400 - n.x) * CONFIG.dispersal;
  n.vy += (300 - n.y) * CONFIG.dispersal;

  n.vx *= CONFIG.amplification;
  n.vy *= CONFIG.amplification;

  n.x += n.vx;
  n.y += n.vy;
}
```

So overall itâ€™s a **force-directed graph layout** centered on the screen.

